Name: requestNotificationPermission

Type: command

Syntax: requestNotificationPermission

Summary:
Asks the operating system to grant permission to display notifications.

Introduced: 1.0.0

OS: mac, windows, linux

Platforms: desktop

Example:
-- Request permission when the app first launches
on startUp
    if notificationPermission() is not "granted" then
        requestNotificationPermission
    end if
end startUp

Example:
-- Handle the result in the card's script
on notificationPermissionGranted
    -- Notifications are now available; show a welcome notification.
    showNotification "Ready" "Notifications are enabled."
end notificationPermissionGranted

on notificationPermissionDenied
    answer "Please enable notifications in System Settings to receive alerts."
end notificationPermissionDenied

Description:
On platforms that require explicit user consent before displaying
notifications (macOS 10.14+), call
<requestNotificationPermission> to trigger the system permission dialog.

The request is handled asynchronously. When the user responds to the
system prompt, HyperXTalk fires one of two messages to the current card
of the default stack:

- <notificationPermissionGranted> — the user approved, or permission was
  already granted.
- <notificationPermissionDenied> — the user declined, or permission was
  previously denied and cannot be re-requested.

On Windows and Linux, permission is always considered granted. Calling
this command on those platforms fires <notificationPermissionGranted>
synchronously without showing any system dialog.

Use <notificationPermission> to query the current permission state
without triggering a prompt.

References: showNotification (command), cancelNotification (command),
cancelAllNotifications (command), notificationPermission (function),
notificationPermissionGranted (message), notificationPermissionDenied (message)

Tags: notifications
